05668nam a2200733Ia 9781478059301DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780593017 a10.1515/97814780593012doi  a(DE-B1597)685449  a(OCoLC)1428234460  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS88b.S458 2024 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a810.9223/eng/2023120600aSituation Critical :bCritique, Theory, and Early American Studies /ced. by Max Cavitch, Brian Connolly. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction: Situation Critical -- tI Theory for Early America -- tOne Psychoanalysis and the Indeterminacy of History -- tTwo Michael Meranze Foucault’s Oedipus -- tII Subjects of Early America -- tThree Ana Schwartz Annoyances, Tolerable and Intolerable -- tFour Michael Wigglesworth’s Queer Orthography -- tFive George Whitefield’s Sexual Character -- tIII Fantasies of Realism -- tSix Secularism, Hypocrisy, and the Afterlives of Thomas Paine -- tSeven No Matter -- tEight Queering Abolition -- tIV Power, Knowledge, Justice -- tNine Equity in the Time of Moby-Dick -- tTen Antebellum or Interbellum? -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to Situation Critical argue for the continued importance of critique to early American studies, pushing back against both reductivist neo-empiricism and so-called postcritique. Bringing together essays by a diverse group of historians and literary scholars, editors Max Cavitch and Brian Connolly demonstrate that critique is about acknowledging that we are never simply writing better or worse accounts of the past, but accounts of the present as well. The contributors examine topics ranging from the indeterminacy of knowledge and history to Black speculative writing and nineteenth-century epistemology, the role of the unconscious in settler colonialism, and early American writing about masturbation, repression, religion, and secularism and their respective influence on morality. The contributors also offer vital new interpretations of major lines of thought in the history of critique—especially those relating to Freud and Foucault—that will be valuable both for scholars of early American studies and for scholars of the humanities and interpretive social sciences more broadly.Contributors. Max Cavitch, Brian Connolly, Matthew Crow, John J. Garcia, Christopher Looby, Michael Meranze, Mark J. Miller, Justine S. Murison, Britt Rusert, Ana Schwartz, Joan W. Scott, Jordan Alexander Stein  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc2DLC. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aAmerican literaturey17th centuryxThemes, motives2DLC. 0aAmerican literaturey17th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aAmerican literaturey18th centuryxThemes, motives2DLC. 0aAmerican literaturey18th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxThemes, motives2DLC. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aCriticismzUnited States2DLC. 0aCriticismzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh1 aCavitch, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavitch, Max, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConnolly, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrow, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1